Package sk.stuba.fiit.martin.szabo.main

Class Main

  • java.lang.Object
    • sk.stuba.fiit.martin.szabo.main.Main
  • public class Main
extends java.lang.Object
    This program implements four different data structures: AVL Tree, Splay Tree, Open Addressing Hashtable, and Separate Chaining Hashtable. Each data structure is designed to store and retrieve data in a specific way.

    AVL Tree is a self-balancing binary search tree. It maintains a balance factor for each node and adjusts the tree structure whenever an insertion or deletion causes the balance factor to become out of balance. This ensures that the height of the tree is always logarithmic and guarantees efficient search, insertion, and deletion operations.

    Splay Tree is another self-balancing binary search tree that reorganizes itself based on the recently accessed nodes. Whenever a node is accessed, it becomes the root of the tree, and the tree is reorganized to minimize the depth of the recently accessed nodes. This provides efficient search times for frequently accessed data.

    Open Addressing Hashtable is a data structure that stores data in an array, using a hash function to map the data to a specific index in the array. If the index is already occupied, the hash function is modified to find the next available index until an empty slot is found. This allows for efficient search, insertion, and deletion of data.

    Separate Chaining Hashtable is another type of Hashtable that uses a LinkedList to store data. Each index in the array stores a pointer to the head of a LinkedList, and data is inserted at the beginning of the list. If multiple items are stored at the same index, they are stored in a LinkedList, ensuring efficient retrieval of data.

    Overall, this program provides a variety of data structures that can be used to store and retrieve data efficiently.
